swiftclient/client.py.message: I'd love to get more mileage out of this block
probably handle some sessions and new auth methods that provide form keystoneauth?

Our minimum-supported keystoneclient is stupid-old (like, 0.7.0) and even that isn't strictly enforced (since it's an optional dep).

This led to us having these crazy import checks, and the exception getting raised around L617 when they fail (but only if you're actually trying to use keystone).

It *also* means that being able to import the v3 client won't be enough to guarantee that keystoneauth1 is available. I'm slightly worried about someone trying to use this while still having an old (pre-2.0.0) keystoneclient installed and hitting a NameError... but then, that came out like 4 or 5 years ago. It's probably fine.

You're correct. I hit this problem when I used pythton-keystoneclient 1.8.1 that won't have a dependence for keystoneauth1 until you install  pythton-keystoneclient>=2.0.0

$ swift stat -v
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/Volumes/Data/charles/Work/SwiftStack/github/python-swiftclient-review/swiftclient/client.py", line 74, in <module>
    from keystoneauth1.identity import v3
ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'keystoneauth1'

During handling of the above exception, another exception occurred:


Try to catch the exception and raise a client error when it uses v3 module but it doesn't exist.

Maybe force the requirement for pythton-keystoneclient>=2.0.0?

Should we have a

 elif os_options.get('auth_type'):
     raise ClientException(...)

here, too, similar to what we did in shell.py?

swiftclient/shell.py.message:
I don't quite like how we add a whole new option (with a heap of expected-to-be-supported values: https://github.com/openstack/keystoneauth/blob/3.18.0/setup.cfg#L41-L61) but only use it to check for one specific case. I'd kind of prefer to just punt to keystoneauth to create a Session for us and go from there...

I think it'd also satisfy some other concerns I have: What if a user expects to be able to use --os-application-credential-name instead of --os-application-credential-id? How much more plumbing and special-casing will we need to support OIDC, or MFA? On the whole, I just *don't want to have to think* about auth, and I'd rather have it be someone else's problem ;-)

I'll play around with it a bit. Maybe this patch will work as a MVP for the CLI in the mean time? OTOH, it's adding more already-published options we need to ensure we're still compatible with as part of any transition...

I saw there is a bunch of options to do auth in keystone, they might have another quest like this. I feel to move the auth to keystone auth is a good idea and just bypass that from swiftcleint, and then we just use the token to communicate with Swift cluster.

Hi Marios,

Many thanks for the review :)

It is not very clear from original commit message or comments in script(# nohup needed as vbmc seems to keep stdin open) why nohup was added in the first place.

but having nohup is actually creating more issues:-

1) If we run command with nohup we cannot determine whether the actual command exits with a non-zero status or not?

example:-

~~~
$ cat file_dont_exists
cat: file_dont_exists: No such file or directory

$ echo $?
1  >>> non-zero status

$ nohup cat file_dont_exists &
[1] 11827
nohup: ignoring input and appending output to 'nohup.out'
[1]+  Exit 1                  nohup cat file_dont_exists

$ echo $?
0  >>> zero status even on the actual command failing

$ cat nohup.out 
cat: file_dont_exists: No such file or directory
~~~

We don't want deployment to succeed even if the qemu vm creation is unsuccessfull so return code from create-node.sh is important here. 

Currently deployment is passing even if some commands in the bash fails. so we have added 'set -e' so that script exits immediately if a command exits with a non-zero status so it would result in deployment failure.



2) Also with nohup, Earlier Ansible deployment failed on vbmc_setup.yaml bash script with below error:-

~~~
Command failed: No domain with matching name node1 was found
~~~

ref:- https://storage.gra.cloud.ovh.net/v1/AUTH_dcaab5e32b234d56b626f72581e3644c/zuul_opendev_logs_887/724119/7/check/tripleo-ci-centos-8-scenario012-standalone/8879b01/logs/undercloud/home/zuul/ansible.log

But node1 was created properly as per:-

https://storage.gra.cloud.ovh.net/v1/AUTH_dcaab5e32b234d56b626f72581e3644c/zuul_opendev_logs_887/724119/7/check/tripleo-ci-centos-8-scenario012-standalone/8879b01/logs/undercloud/home/zuul/create-node-1.log

I am of opinion that because we were creating node1 in background with nohup, it was taking time and node1 was not created till we ran vbmc add for node1.

Removing nohup is solving both the above problems.

The second option is to leverage TLS for all endpoints in the entire deployment, including the overcloud, undercloud, and any systems that natively support TLS. We typically refer to this approach as TLS-everywhere because we use TLS everywhere we can, encrypting as much network traffic as possible. nova is expecting the retry behavior to already handel redeclaring the queus on topic send but we recently have been looking at two issue that i think are realted to the queue not being redeclared by the send when a rabbit host is restared and the compute nodes that were using that host dont automatically redeclare the queue.

restarting the coumpute services fixes the issue but we had been expecting the heatbeat to be enought to fix that and it looks like it may not be.

simiarly for the eventlet/wsgi issue we were having we had some concners that the recovery that was happening was not always redeclaring the queues properly so we proably woudl want this to be handelded internally by oslo messaging
to actully have the behavior we thought was being guranteed by the auto retry on publish that is already done.

> the main drawback to this approch is that it requires client to set
 > this option as it not used by default.
Yes, we have to maintain the compatibility with the current behavior, we can't enable it by default.

I got what you mean but, like Melanie, I didn't understand the -1

> the main drawback to this approch is that it requires client to set
 > this option as it not used by defualt.

Is your -1 because you are suggesting this patch go ahead and set the mandatory flag by default instead of passing generic options through?
sorry yes the -1 was to suggest we should not nessisarly push this to the caller to manage the retry and i wanted to discuss if we should handle this internally.

we can handle this in nova i guess by trying to recreate the exchange and queue then submit the message again.

we may want the flexibility for the client to make that choice but if we have not hit the retry limit then we may want oslo to do that on the client behalf?

i guess either is fine i just would have expected ensure
to try and recover from this if the retry limit is not hit.

ya thats fair and its why it was a question of should we handel this internally or not.

if we wanted to handle this internally it could certainly be a separate patch but we can also try and use this from nova and see if this is something we would want to use selectively or for all calls and just that to inform if internal handling is a useful feature to add later.

in nova's case its unclear if we want to create the queue if id does not exist when the api tries to call a compute node.

nova will only call a compute node if it exist in its database which means it should have a topic queue for the api to send a call too. but as was discussed in the original bug creating the queue could result in the queue filling up if the agent never retruns so its not clear that is the right thing to do.

If we're not 100% sure what the usage pattern for this is going to look like, I'm +1 on implementing the simple(-ish) thing and then pulling common patterns out of consumers once we start to understand how they're going to use it.

>we may want the flexibility for the client to make that choice

basically Yes.
That's the reasons:

Yeah, none of this is public, but I'd rather keep the names consistent across drivers so if someone does start passing the argument by name it doesn't break on some drivers because they have a different name for it.

We should document what options are recognized by a given function once we start to actually use this, so we could just add a note that options is ignored for these particular functions.

In most languages, "_xx" means unused parameters. Since "options" here is not used (yet) I put "_". 
If you prefer I can remove it btw.
ty!

that idiom is not used in python because the paramater names are part of the public signature of the function which means if you use it in the future and remvoe the _ you are technically breaking the public api compatablity.

this would therefor cause issue with inheritence as the name change in the base could break invocations of the overload on the drived class.

in languages like java or c or c++ where we do not have named paramaters teh parmater name in the function defintion is not part of function signiture, only the types are but for lanaguge like python or c# where they are its problematic.
